snippet.textDisplay:
Had completely flooded Freelander 2.0 diesel, water levels were 1 meter above the roof and it was in the water for about 2 weeks.

It didn't cost to much to repair but it took me whole summer to get it done. Now, I have to say this car is really weird. Water in the engine and the belt bearings that are dead means water level was hood or more, but the enterior looks good and electronics work, so yeah, really weird. Maybe someone washed it and replaced electronics?

Anyway, the main issue is you will have problems over time, even though you fix it now parts will die off one by one. Water that got in is not clean water but has a bunch of sand in it and other stuff. pretty much every moving part will be compromised. I had steering rack gone, steering pump, diesel pump, literally every wheel bearing, every belt bearing etc. I'm not sure what is the deal with this car but be aware that every moving system that got this dirty water in will give you problems at some point.

snippet.textDisplay: Something else that needs to be checked on a flood car are the wheel bearings. A friend bought a restored flooded Ford and several months after he bought it, the front left wheel bearing failed. When it was checked, it still had water in it from the flood, so whoever salvaged the car, had not checked the wheel bearings for water and cleaned and re-greased them. Result - new front wheel bearings needed.
snippet.textOriginal: Something else that needs to be checked on a flood car are the wheel bearings. A friend bought a restored flooded Ford and several months after he bought it, the front left wheel bearing failed. Result - new front wheel bearings needed.
